The length of the vector quantifies the transcription activity of the cells. Longer length implies the cells express more genes at higher levels. The mutual angle between two vectors quantifies the similarity of the two cells. More stochasticity in gene expression of the examined cells leads to larger mutual angles. The mutual distance between two vectors is a combined measure of cell activity and gene expression stochasticity. We calculated the mean of the mutual distances between all pairs of cells for each cell type of each sample. To see their relation, consider a D dimensional Gaussian distribution:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
